    "name": "COU1: Non-cannulated construct compression-bending prediction",
    "description": "FEA predicts construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending. Validated by direct comparison to bench testing (N=11 constructs across two laboratories). Model influence MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence MEDIUM (pedicle screw fracture leads to revision surgery, not death).",
    "intendedUse": "Demonstrate that the FEA modeling framework reproduces experimental compression-bending behavior of a non-cannulated pedicle screw construct within pre-established acceptance bounds (<10% QoI difference, E/uval < 1.96).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "decisionConsequence": "Medium",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "hasApplicabilityConstraint": {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/cou/cou1-noncannulated/applicability-constraint",
      "type": "ApplicabilityConstraint",
      "name": "Applicability constraint: non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw under quasi-static F1717 loading",
      "description": "This COU applies exclusively to non-cannulated pedicle screws with nominal diameter 7.5 mm and thread pitch 3.0 mm, assessed under quasi-static ASTM F1717 compression-bending loading in a surrogate vertebral body fixture. Dynamic loading, fatigue regimes, cannulated variants, and screws with diameter outside 7.0–8.0 mm are explicitly out of scope. The FEA material model is validated only for Ti-6Al-4V ELI alloy with yield strength 860–950 MPa."
    },
    "hasOperatingEnvelope": {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/cou/cou1-noncannulated/operating-envelope",
      "type": "OperatingEnvelope",
      "name": "Operating envelope: F1717 quasi-static compression-bending bounds",
      "description": "Crosshead displacement rate: 5 mm/min ± 0.5 mm/min. Applied compressive force range: 0–2500 N. Bending moment arm: 44 mm (ASTM F1717 nominal). Ambient temperature: 20–25 °C. Surrogate vertebral body block material: ultra-high-molecular-weight polyethylene (UHMWPE), Shore D 60–65. Screw insertion torque: 4.0–6.0 N·m. Maximum displacement recorded: 40 mm. All tests conducted in dry air; no saline immersion for this COU."
    }
  },
  "hasSensitivityAnalysis": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/sensitivity/cou1-sa-01",
    "type": "SensitivityAnalysis",
    "name": "Sensitivity analysis: material property and mesh density effects on predicted construct stiffness",
    "description": "A one-at-a-time sensitivity study varied Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus ±5% (107–118 GPa), yield strength ±8% (793–1026 MPa), and element edge length from 0.3 mm to 1.2 mm at the screw–rod interface. Construct stiffness QoI varied by at most 3.1% across the modulus range and 1.8% across mesh densities, confirming that the 0.5 mm baseline mesh and nominal material properties are not dominant uncertainty sources; the largest sensitivity driver was found to be the screw–UHMWPE block contact friction coefficient (μ = 0.15–0.35), which produced a 6.4% stiffness variation and was subsequently treated as a calibrated parameter bounded by experimental torque measurements."
  },
